      <section class="section--bulimia">
        <div class="wrap--content">
          <h1 class="heading--1">Binge eating disorder (<abbr title="Binge Eating Disorder">B.E.D.</abbr>) is different from bulimia nervosa</h1>
          <h2 class="heading--2"><abbr title="Binge Eating Disorder">B.E.D.</abbr> is not associated with compensatory behaviors like purging or excessive exercise, or with dietary restriction, though frequent dieting may be reported<sup>1</sup></h2>
        </div>
      </section>
      <section class="section--overeating">
        <div class="wrap--content">
          <h1 class="heading--1"><abbr title="Binge Eating Disorder">B.E.D.</abbr> is different from overeating</h1>
          <h2 class="heading--2">While overeating is a challenge for many Americans, recurrent binge eating is much less common, far more severe, and is associated with significant physical and psychological problems<sup>2</sup></h2>
        </div>
      </section>
      <section class="section--obesity">
        <div class="wrap--content">
          <h1 class="heading--1"><abbr title="Binge Eating Disorder">B.E.D.</abbr> is different from obesity</h1>
          <h2 class="heading--2">Although <abbr title="Binge Eating Disorder">B.E.D.</abbr> can be associated with increased weight, it occurs in normal-weight, overweight, and obese adults<sup>3</sup></h2>
        </div>
      </section>
      <section class="section--majority">
        <div class="wrap--content">
          <h1 class="heading--2">The majority of adults with <abbr title="Binge Eating Disorder">B.E.D.</abbr> are not obese*<sup>3</sup>:</h1>
          <div class="chart-wrap">
            <div class="chart"></div>
            <div class="label top left">
              <div class="num">19.0%</div>
              <div class="clas">are Normal-<br>weight</div>
              <div class="footnote">Body mass index <br>(BMI) 18.5-24.9</div>
            </div>
            <div class="label top right">
              <div class="num">16.2%</div>
              <div class="clas">are Very<br>Severely Obese</div>
              <div class="footnote">Body mass index<br>(BMI) &gt;40.0</div>
            </div>
            <div class="label bottom left">
              <div class="num">35.7%</div>
              <div class="clas">are Overweight</div>
              <div class="footnote">Body mass index <br>(BMI) 25.0-29.9</div>
            </div>
            <div class="label bottom right">
              <div class="num">29.2%</div>
              <div class="clas">are Moderately to<br>Severely Obese</div>
              <div class="footnote">Body mass index<br>(BMI) 30.0-39.9</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
      <section class="section--compared">
        <div class="wrap--content">
          <h1 class="heading--2 top">Compared with weight-matched obese adults without <abbr title="Binge Eating Disorder">B.E.D.</abbr>, obese adults with <abbr title="Binge Eating Disorder">B.E.D.</abbr> eat more calories in studies of how people eat and show<sup>1</sup>:</h1>
          <ul class="square line">
            <li>More functional impairment</li>
            <li>Greater self-reported distress</li>
            <li>Impaired quality of life</li>
            <li>More coexisting psychiatric conditions</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="statistic-box">
            <h2 class="heading--2">At rates similar to those with bulimia and anorexia, adults with <abbr title="Binge Eating Disorder">B.E.D.</abbr> may have coexisting psychiatric and physical conditions like bipolar disorders, depressive disorders, anxiety disorders, substance use disorders, and obesity<sup>1</sup></h2>
            <h4 class="heading--2">Lifetime psychiatric comorbidity associated with <abbr title="Binge Eating Disorder">B.E.D.</abbr>*<sup>3</sup></h4>
            <div class="statistic">
              <div class="num">79%</div>
              <div class="text">met criteria for <em>at least one </em>other psychiatric disorder</div>
            </div>
            <div class="statistic">
              <div class="num">49%</div>
              <div class="text">met criteria for <em>three or more </em>other psychiatric disorders</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p data-note="*" class="footnote">Data (based on Version 3.0 of the World Health Organization Composite International Diagnostic Interview and DSM-IV&reg; criteria) from an eating disorder–assessed subsample (n=2,980) of the National Comorbidity Survey Replication, a nationally representative face-to-face household survey of English-speaking adults aged ≥18 years.<sup>3</sup></p>
